r, Oxfordshire, England","Swalcliffe, Oxfordshire, England":"Swalcliffe, Oxfordshire, England"},"en":{"1530–1578":"1530–1578","1535–1587":"1535–1587","1555–1613":"1555–1613","1557–Male":"1557–Deceased","1559–Female":"1559–Deceased","1561–1610":"1561–1610","1563–Male":"1563–Deceased","1564–1587":"1564–1587","–Male":"Deceased","1561":"1561","1571":"1571","4 April 1578":"4 April 1578","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1613":"1613","1557":"1557","1535":"1535","1578":"1578","1555":"1555","1610":"1610","1587":"1587","1564":"1564","1530":"1530","1563":"1563","1549":"1549","1559":"1559","England":"England","Sibford Gower, Oxfordshire, England":"Sibford Gower, Oxfordshire, England","Swalcliffe, Oxfordshire, England":"Swalcliffe, Oxfordshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Faxon","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: Warwickshire dialect variant of <b>Foxon</b>, which is either a patronymic from the Middle English personal name <i>Folk</i> (see   Foulkes  ) or a habitational name from Foxton in Leicestershire."],"variants":[{"name":"Fawson","meanings":["English: probably a variant of   Faxon  ."]},{"name":"Foulkes","meanings":["English: variant of   Foulks  ."]}]},{"name":"Richard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Rikert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]},{"name":"Rickert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":19,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705202,"age":28,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705205,"age":39,"year":"1569","julianDay":2294126,"title":"State Lottery","description":"A State Lottery was recorded in 1569. The tickets were sold at St. Paul's Cathedral in London.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705206,"age":41,"year":"1571","julianDay":2294856,"title":"The Royal Exchange is Organized","description":"The Royal Exchange was organized in January 1571 by Sir Thomas Gresham. Gresham is known as the father of English banking.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Richard Faxon was born in 1530, in England. He married Elizabeth Sheppard in 1555, in England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1578, in Sibford Gower, Oxfordshire, England, at the age of 48, and was buried in Swalcliffe, Oxfordshire, England."},"et":{"1530–1578":"1530–1578","1535–1587":"1535–1587","1555–1613":"1555–1613","1557–Male":"1557–Surnud","1559–Female":"1559–Surnud","1561–1610":"1561–1610","1563–Male":"1563–Surnud","1564–1587":"1564–1587","–Male":"Surnud","1561":"1561","1571":"1571","4 April 1578":"4. aprill 1578","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1613":"1613","1557":"1557","1535":"1535","1578":"1578","1555":"1555","1610":"1610","1587":"1587","1564":"1564","1530":"1530","1563":"1563","1549":"1549","1559":"1559","England":"England","Sibford Gower, Oxfordshire, England":"Sibford Gower, Oxfordshire, England","Swalcliffe, Oxfordshire, England":"Swalcliffe, Oxfordshire, England"},"fi":{"1530–1578":"1530–1578","1535–1587":"1535–1587","1555–1613":"1555–1613","1557–Male":"1557–Kuollut","1559–Female":"1559–Kuollut","1561–1610":"1561–1610","1563–Male":"1563–Kuollut","1564–1587":"1564–1587","–Male":"Kuollut","1561":"1561","1571":"1571","4 April 1578":"4. huhtikuuta 1578","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1613":"1613","1557":"1557","1535":"1535","1578":"1578","1555":"1555","1610":"1610","1587":"1587","1564":"1564","1530":"1530","1563":"1563","1549":"1549","1559":"1559","England":"England","Sibford Gower, Oxfordshire, England":"Sibford Gower, Oxfordshire, England","Swalcliffe, Oxfordshire, England":"Swalcliffe, Oxfordshire, England"},"fr":{"1530–1578":"1530–1578","1535–1587":"1535–1587","1555–1613":"1555–1613","1557–Male":"1557–Décédé","1559–Female":"1559–Décédée","1561–1610":"1561–1610","1563–Male":"1563